\subsection{Notes on the rewrite rules}

\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Substitution, rule \rulename{bind}.}
  \begin{itemize}
    %\item \rulename{bind} does not discard the heap binding, because it may be needed,
    %  in \rulename{if-true} and \rulename{for}.
   \item We could use a rule that substitutes in just one place (a la Ariola).
   \item Rule \rulename{bind} fires only if the variable is equated to a
     \emph{value}, and values can freely be duplicated without duplicating
     work, so \rulename{bind} does not duplicate work.
   \item The $x \notin \freevars{v}$ is an occures check, which prevents cyclic data structures.
   \end{itemize}
\item Rule \rulename{def-elim} removes up |defKW| bindings, but only when they are empty. Every variable introduced must be, at some point, eliminated using \rulename{bind}.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Unification}

Rules \rulename{ucon} and \rulename{utup} do conventional unification, decomposing
tuples where necessary.  Notice that |e_1 == e_2| reduces to its unified value.  For example,
|(3==3) + 7| reduces to |10|.

In rule \rulename{ucon} there are two uses of ``$=$'', but they are different!  The ``|k_1 == k_2|''
on the LHS is part of the syntax of Verse. In contrast
the ``$k_1 = k_2$'' in the side-condition is ``real'' equality: it means that |k_1| and |k_2| are the
same constant.

Rules \rulename{bind}, \rulename{def-float}, and \rulename{swap} come into play when variables are involved.
First, \rulename{bind} says that when within the scope of |x|, we find an equation that unifies it with a value |v|, we can substitute that value for |x| and eliminate |x| completely.
The side condition $\freevars{v} \disjoint \{x\}$ ensuress that |v| does not mention |x| itself -- the ``occurs check''. This way we never have cyclic values.

Crucially, note that $X$ does not look inside |oneKW|, |allKW|, or choice (|choice|).
For example
$$ |def x (one (x==3); x)| $$
does
not unify |x| via \rulename{bind}; only variables bound by the \emph{innermost enclosing \hexp{}} can be unified.
Nor does $X$ look inside choices.  For example,
|def x (x==2 choice x==3)| does not unify |x| via \rulename{bind}.

Rule \rulename{swap} swaps |(hnf=x)| to |(x=hnf)| to allow rule \rulename{bind} to fire.
We just need to be careful that we cannot swap |(x=y)| to |(y=x)| and back forever; hence
using |hnf| rather than |v| in this rule.

Rule \rulename{def-float} expands the scope of variables within the current execution context $X$, and \rulename{def-merge} combines all variables with the same scope in a single |defKW|. This allows \rulename{bind} to fire on any of these variable. For example in
    $$ |def x  (dots x dots(def z (dots(x==(3,z))dots))dots)| $$
it would be dangerous if \rulename{bind} could substitute |(3,z)| for |x| right away, because |z| is not in scope everywhere where |x| is. But after floating and merging we get
    $$ |def (x,z)  (dots x dots(dots(x==(3,z))dots)dots)| $$
and now we can safely invoke \rulename{bind} on |x|.

One might expect to see the innocent looking rule \rulename{uvar} allowing $|x == x| \movesto |x|$, but such a rule would lead to non-confluence. Consider |def x (x = (y => y); (x == x))|. If we use \rulename{bind} first, we will unify two lambda values, which reduces to |wrong| per \rulename{unify-wrong}, but if we use \rulename{uvar} first, the term would reduce to |(y => y)|.

\subsection{Choice and failure}

Rule \rulename{choose} is the crucial one: it duplicates the entire |defKW| context.  But note the
\emph{choice-free} context |CX|!  For example, the expression
$$
|def (x,y) ((x == (3 choice 4)) ; (y == (9 choice 2)); (x,y))|
$$
should yield the values |(3,9)|, |(3,2)|, |(4,9)|, |(4,2)|, in that order.
To get the order right, we must apply \rulename{choose} to the first choice |(3 choice 4)| first, and only
then to the second |(9 choice 2)|.  This is achieved by using |CX| in \rulename{choose} to ensure that only the
\emph{leftmost} choice can be chosen.

Rule \rulename{fail} collapes an expression with a nested |fail| into a single |fail|.  It uses the |X| evaluation
context, which looks more deeply into an expression than does |CX|.  For example
$$
|def (x,y) ((x == (3 choice 4)) ; (y == (9 choice 2)); fail; (x,y))|
$$
can fail immediately; we don't need to perform the choices for |x| and |y| first, because they will all fail.
The use of |X| also means that a |def h (2, fail plus 3, 7)| will collapse to |fail| by \rulename{fail};
we do not need rules like $|fail plus e| \movesto |fail|$.

But note that $X$ does not look inside choices.  For example, |def h (fail choice e)| does not collapse
to |fail| by \rulename{fail}.

\subsection{Functions and application}

Rule \rulename{app-lam} is our $\beta$-reduction rule. It can be applied even if the argument |e_2| is not (yet) a value, and unifies the parameter with the results from that expression. If |e_2| happens to already be a value |v|, then this yields the same as the simple and beautiful $\beta$-reduction rule |applyx (x => e) v| $\movesto$ |subst e x v|.

A recursive definition gets unrolled one step when it is used in the function position of |apply| by rule \rulename{app-rec}.
If the body of the recursive definition is a function then reduction will eventually proceed.

A tuples/array behaves like a (finite) function, and can be applied to a numeric value
in \rulename{app-arr} to index it: |applyx (array (v_0,dots v_n)) k| evaluates to |v_k| if |k| is a number within the bounds of the array, or to |fail| otherwise. But since \rulename{app-arr} is defined via choice, the expression |y = applyx a x| actually enumerates the positions and values of all entries of the array |a|. For example, |all (def x (42 = applyx a x; x))| finds the indicies of all entries in |a| that are 42.


\subsection{Conditionals}

In Verse, an |if|-expression does not evaluate its condition to a Boolean true or false.  Instead
it tests whether its condition succeeds (i.e. returns one or more values) or fails (returning no values). The essence of this check is captured in the |one e| construct, which evaluates to the \emph{first} value returned by |e|. The conventional |if e_1 then e_2 else e_3| construct can be built on top of |oneKW|.

For example |if (x=3) then e_1 else e_2| tries to unify |x| and |3|; if that succeds (returning one value, namely |3|)
the |if| returns |e_1|, otherwise it returns |e_2|.

Comparision operators succeed or fail, rather than returning a Boolean
(as in most languages). For example |(x>3)| suceeds if |x| is greater
than 3, returning |x|; and fails if not.

It is very important that in |one ((x=3;1) choice 2)| we
treat |x| as ``rigid'': the conditional is intended to \emph{test}
|x|'s value, rather \emph{giving} |x| its value!  That is why rule \rulename{bind}
does not look inside an |oneKW| (look at the syntax of context |X| used in that rule).

\subsection{|wrong| and the verifier}
Some expressions don't make sense, such as using a number as a function in function application, or comparing two lambda values. These expressions are wrong in a different way than failing expressions and stuck expressions:
\begin{itemize}
\item The expression |(1=2)|, for example in an |if| conditional, is benign and its reduction to |fail| is part of the normal course of program execution.
\item The expression |def x (applyx (one (x = 1; (y => (x = 1)))) ())| is stuck, as no rule can make progress, but there is nothing obivously wrong with this program.
\end{itemize}

To clearly identify wrong terms, we introduce the special construct |wrong| to the syntax, and rewrite bad expressions to |wrong| using the rules in Figure \ref{fig:wrong-axioms}.

The introduction of |wrong| is crucial to give a specification to a \emph{verifier}, which is a static analysis that rules out wrong reduction; according to the motto “verified programs don’t go wrong”.

But not every |wrong| is wrong: because we allow reduction everywhere, even in eventually unused code, we must allow for |wrong| to appear temporarily, as in this reduction:
\[
|one (1 choice (applyx 2 3))| \movesto |one (1 choice wrong)| \movesto |1|
\]

Only those occurrences of |wrong| that are “needed” matter. To identify those, we can extend our reduction semantics with the |wrong| propagation rules in Figure~\ref{fig:wrong-propagation}. With these in place, the verifier will guarantee that the overall program does not evaluate to |wrong|, even though subexpressions may be |wrong|. Therefore, the propagation rules are irrelevant for the execution of verified program.

Note that the rule \rulename{wrong} can compete with \rulename{fail}. This is ok: The specification of the verifier forbids the existene of \emph{any} bad reduction.

\subsection{The Equality Principle}

Verse cleaves to the following principle.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{The Equality Principle (EP)}.
For any choice-free, side-effect-free expression |e|, and values |v_1| and |v_2|,
if |(e = v_1)| is inhabited, and |(e = v_2)| is inhabited, then |v_1|=|v_2|.
\end{quote}
For example suppose |misBehaves = t => def x x|, so that (if we are not careful) the call |misBehaves()| returns
a fresh, unbound logical variable.  Now |(misBehaves() = 3)| and |(misBehaves() = 4)| will both succeed (be inhabited),
but 3 is not equal to 4.  So this wouldn't satisfy the EP.

Another way of putting this is that |=| behaves as an equivalence relation in Verse.

\subsection{Source Verse}

In the Verse source language we do not write explicit |defKW|s. Instead, they are added
by a simple preprocessing step, that introduces a variable |x| in the innermost
|defKW| that encloses all its uses.
\simon{It's hard to say more until we say more about Source Verse.}

In the arms of a choice |(e_1 choice e_2)| we add a |def h e_1| around |e_1| if
|e_1| introduces any new variables; and similarly |e_2|.
\simon{This was a nice little simplification.}

