  The evaluation of |add^(x,1)| is stuck, and hence so is the unification
  |(y==add^(x,1))|.  But the evaluation context |X| allows us to apply rule \rulename{bind}
  in the \emph{second} argument of sequencing, which gives a value to |x| in the heap.
  That allows the |add| to proceed.  So ``later'' instructions can unblock ``earlier'' ones.
\end{example}

